  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1315592061" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1315592061" />
    <a title="Matthew Quann" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22699228-matthew-quann"><img alt="Matthew Quann" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1528393487p2/22699228.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1315592061?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matthew Quann" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matthew Quann" href="/user/show/22699228-matthew-quann">Matthew Quann</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/31568629-the-orphan-master-s-son">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22699228-matthew-quann?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22699228-matthew-quann?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22699228-matthew-quann?shelf=funny-stuff">funny-stuff</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22699228-matthew-quann?shelf=whip-smart">whip-smart</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22699228-matthew-quann?shelf=pulitzers">pulitzers</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22699228-matthew-quann?shelf=2020-pulitzer-challenge">2020-pulitzer-challenge</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1315592061" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8959817081924363365">There&apos;s been times when I&apos;ve read a novel that I&apos;ve loved so much that I struggle to articulate my thoughts in anything other than exclamations, growls, and excessive hand gestures. It&apos;s sort of like running into a person at a party who is too drunk but seems to have vital information to relay, but for books. Book drunk, I guess. <br/><br/>So, when I finished <i>The Orphan Master&apos;s Son</i> yesterday afternoon, pondered about it all evening, and found it still rolling it around in my brain before sleep I knew tha</span>
  <span id="freeText8959817081924363365" style="display:none">There's been times when I've read a novel that I've loved so much that I struggle to articulate my thoughts in anything other than exclamations, growls, and excessive hand gestures. It's sort of like running into a person at a party who is too drunk but seems to have vital information to relay, but for books. Book drunk, I guess. <br /><br />So, when I finished <i>The Orphan Master's Son</i> yesterday afternoon, pondered about it all evening, and found it still rolling it around in my brain before sleep I knew that I'd have to keep this review compact. It's my favourite book I've read this year, and the best Pulitzer Prize winner I've read in years. Adam Johnson works through so many different genres, styles, and POVs that my head spun, but the reading remains smooth and never felt like random elements mashed together. <br /><br />I can't remember the last time I read a book where I'd routinely shout: "I can't believe what's happening!" My wife kept asking me to keep it down while she worked away at her own book. That's just the thing though: you don't know what it's like until you read it! The book goes from being surprising to believably-absurd in the span of a few paragraphs. I never felt like I had firm ground under my feet while reading <i>The Orphan Master's Son</i>, and in that way it reads like a thriller.<br /><br />The breadth and scope of <i>The Orphan Master's Son</i> makes it an astonishing literary achievement, but its readability and relentless pace make it a true stand-out. It's a book that'll I recommend to people at parties and pass along to people who have only a fleeting interest in reading. I loved this book through and through, and I'd love to talk you into reading it, but you're just going to have to take my word and pick it up!<br /><br /><b>This is the fourth book of my 2020 Pulitzer Challenge!</b></span>
  <a data-text-id="8959817081924363365" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

